That’s actually a profound observation, and it’s one of the strangest ordinary facts about life.

“I eat a potato and it becomes me.”

At first glance it’s obvious. But if you sit with it, it’s remarkable.

The potato doesn’t just fuel you. Parts of it literally become your body.

* Its carbon atoms become part of your muscles, skin, brain, or fat.
* Its nitrogen may end up in amino acids that become proteins.
* Its phosphorus may become part of your DNA or the ATP your cells use for energy.
* Over time, many of the atoms that make up “you” were recently part of plants, animals, water, or the atmosphere.

Life is a continuous process of reconstruction. The boundary of “you” is more like a maintained pattern than a fixed collection of matter.

This idea resonates with several traditions and scientific perspectives:

* Metabolism: Living organisms continually replace their material while preserving their organization.
* Ship of Theseus: If every plank is replaced, is it still the same ship? Your body performs this replacement constantly.
* Developmental biology: Your identity persists because of the continuity of processes, not because the atoms remain the same.

It also connects nicely to something you’ve emphasized in your Pantheon work: preserving invariants while allowing the substrate to change. The implementation changes; the organizing pattern persists.

In a poetic sense, you could say:

The potato didn’t disappear. It changed stories.

It stopped being a potato and started participating in the pattern called “me.”

That’s one of the deepest lessons biology offers: organisms are not static objects—they’re ongoing processes that borrow matter from the world, organize it for a while, and eventually return it.